Ä¶<p>A. absolutely have something to say, and a blog is a great place to say it, and..<p>B. The Internet is a huge place. People <em>will</em> find your site and read it, no matter how niche it is, or how poorly designed, or how seemingly poorly written. There‚Äôs no thought you could have that couldn‚Äôt educate someone else out there and nothing you could write about that there isn‚Äôt some community out there that would have similar thoughts.<p>As for the other reasons folks don‚Äôt have a site‚Ä¶<ol><li><p><a href="https://pages.github.com">Github Pages</a> (and some other platforms) is 100% free (so if expense is an issue then it doesn‚Äôt need to be)<li><p>There are <a href="https://shellsharks.com/indieweb#hosting">more hosting providers</a> than ever these days, many of which make it dead simple to get started, so don‚Äôt let complexity be a stopping point. You can always start real simple and get more complex as you go.<li><p>Time may be the biggest hurdle. I would just say that a blog isn‚Äôt something you need to maintain or publish regularly. Just put something up and post when you have time. Posts can be short, they can be sloppy, they can be whatever, Since you own the site, you can always edit something poorly written later too.</ol><p>For everything else, you could check out my post about ‚ÄúWhy I Blog. You Should Too!‚Äù for other advice/inspiration. Cheers!<p><a href="https://shellsharks.com/you-should-blog">https://shellsharks.com/you-should-blog</a></div><div style="bottom:-5px; text-align:right;font-size:0.75em;"><i class="ph ph-pencil"></i> 287</div><hr style="opacity:35%;margin-top: 10px;margin-bottom: 10px;width:75%;" /><div id="info" class="wrapper"><div class="box 1" style="background-color:color-mix(in srgb, var(--mastodon-color) 10%, var(--background-color));"><div><i class="ph ph-map-pin-area" title="Posted from"></i> <span id="posted-from" style="font-size:0.75em;">Ivory for MacOS</span></div><div><i class="ph ph-broadcast"></i><span st